entry.content:
High resolution data can pose problems in memory requirements, expecially in higher dimensions. We explore a simple way of reducing a 2d array by clustering together neighbouring elements that are within a given standard deviation. The function recursively groups together data points until the standard deviation cirteria is not satisfied anymore. The resulting data structure is also known as a Quadtree.

In [2]:
def divide(data, std):
    '''Divide 2d array up such that the standard deviaiton in each cell is < std
    
    Paramters
    ---------
    data : 2d-array
    std : float
    '''
    if np.isscalar(data):
        return data
    if np.std(data) < std:
        return np.mean(data)

    x_middle = data.shape[0] // 2
    y_middle = data.shape[1] // 2
    
    return [divide(data[:x_middle, :y_middle], std),
            divide(data[x_middle:, :y_middle], std),
            divide(data[:x_middle, y_middle:], std),
            divide(data[x_middle:, y_middle:], std)]

To illustrate it we generate a 1024x1024 test data

In [3]:
N = 1024
x = np.cos(np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, N))
y = np.cos(np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, N))
test_data = np.outer(x,y)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7,7))
ax.imshow(test_data)
ax.set_title('Original');
In [4]:
partition = divide(test_data, 0.02)

The result is a nested list, and each element has four entries,

[[child1, child2, child3, child4], ...]

or in case of a leafe it is the resulting number as a float.

Reconstruction Original¶

In order to reconstruct the original image from this quadtree format, we can define a helper function to lookup the value at any position x,y.

In [5]:
def lookup(partition, x, y, x_low, x_high, y_low, y_high):
    '''Lookup value in partitioned data at position x and y
    '''
    if not isinstance(partition, list):
        return partition
    
    x_middle = x_low + (x_high - x_low) // 2
    y_middle = y_low + (y_high - y_low) // 2
    
    lx = x >= x_middle
    ly = y >= y_middle
    
    if ly:
        if lx:
            return lookup(partition[3], x, y, x_middle, x_high, y_middle, y_high)
        return lookup(partition[2], x, y, x_low, x_middle, y_middle, y_high)
    if lx:
        return lookup(partition[1], x, y, x_middle, x_high, y_low, y_middle)
    return lookup(partition[0], x, y, x_low, x_middle, y_low, y_middle)

Let's first see how the resulting partition looks like. The following image shows adjacent cells that are grouped together in the same color. Where the original image has small variations, the patches are bigger - as expected.

In [8]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7,7))
ax.imshow(reconstructed_indices, cmap='Set3')
ax.set_title('Partition');

The following compares the reconstructed image to the original together with the error.

In [9]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(20,8))

im = ax[0].imshow(reconstructed_img)
ax[0].set_title('Recosntructed Image')
plt.colorbar(im, ax=ax[0])

im = ax[1].imshow(reconstructed_img-test_data, cmap='RdBu')
ax[1].set_title('Error')
plt.colorbar(im, ax=ax[1]);

and the distributuion of errors looks like this:

In [10]:
plt.hist((reconstructed_img-test_data).ravel(), bins=100);

So what is the comprression that we achieved?¶

Just from the number of elements in our list, we are at 9951, this is compared to the 1024x1024 original array. But the nested list is an inefficient way of storage compared to numpy arrays, so in order to accurately compute the size of the full object, I use this function. In our example the nested list has a size of 7.6% of the original data.
